03796nam a22004575i 9781501733970DE-B159720210324034602.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210324t20191994nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017339707 a10.7591/97815017339702doi  a(DE-B1597)533856  a(OCoLC)1129174943  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOE0130002bisacsh1 aDavidson, Olga M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPoet and Hero in the Persian Book of Kings /cOlga M. Davidson. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMyth and Poetics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART I. THE POET AND HIS POETRY -- t1. The Authority of Ferdowsi the Poet -- t2. The Authority ofFerdowsi's Shāhnāma -- t3. Ferdowsi's Oral Poetic Heritage -- tPART II. THE HERO -- t4. Book of Kings, Epic of Heroes -- t5. King and Hero, Shāh and Pahlavān -- t6. Rostam, Guardian of Sovereignty -- t7. The Concept of Premature and Immature Fatherhood in the Story of Rostam and Sohrāb -- t8. Father-Son Dioscurism as a Model of Authority in the Shāhnāma -- t9. Feasting and Fighting: Ultimate Occasions for Hero and Poet -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA masterpiece of Persian Classical epic, the Shahnama or Book of Kings was composed by Abu'l-Qasem Ferdowsi at the beginning of the eleventh century. Because the Shahnama presents itself as a chronicle of the reigns of the shahs from the primordial founders to the Sasanian dynasty which ended in 651, scholarly attention has centered on the question of its historical accuracy. Addressing the literary as well as the historical and mythological aspects of the Shahnama, Olga M. Davidson makes this centerpiece of Iranian culture accessible to Western readers.Drawing on recent work in epic studies and oral poetics, Davidson considers analogies with Classical and medieval European narratives as she investigates the poem's social contexts. Her interpretation of the Shahnama focuses on both the figure of the poet himself and on his protagonists-the superhuman hero Rostam and the historical or historicized shahs. Exploring the Shahnama as an example of court poetry designed to glorify the idea of empire, Davidson identifies as a driving force of Ferdowsi's narrative a strong current of antagonism between king and hero. Ironically, she shows, it is the epic hero himself who poses the greatest threat to the concept of kingship that he is sworn to defend.Poet and Hero in the Persian Book of Kings will be welcomed by readers working in such fields as comparative literature, Middle Eastern Studies, folklore, literary theory, and comparative religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mrz 2021) 4aPoetry & Criticism. 7aPOETRY / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173397040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501733970423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501733970.jpg  aGBV-deGruyter-alles